context: Since the coronations in 1066 of both King Harold and William the Conqueror, coronations of English and British monarchs were held in the abbey. In <a1_0><b6_0>1216<b6_0/><a1_0/>, Henry III was unable to be crowned in London when he first came to the throne, because the <a2_0><b7_0>French prince Louis<b7_0/><a2_0/> had taken control of the city, and so the king was crowned in <a0_0><b5_0>Gloucester Cathedral<b5_0/><a0_0/>. This coronation was deemed by <a3_0><b8_0>the Pope<b8_0/><a3_0/> to be improper, and a further coronation was held in the abbey on 17 May 1220. <a4_0><b9_0>The Archbishop of Canterbury<b9_0/><a4_0/> is the traditional cleric in the coronation ceremony.[citation needed]
